{code}

h2. Existing Partial Workaround
One can suppress the first error message by setting the class below as FATAL on Logging and Properties, given it is the one generating such logging:
{code}
com.atlassian.confluence.extra.webdav
{code}

h2. Missing Workaround
The second error message is thrown at the following class/line:
{code:java}
com.atlassian.confluence.extra.webdav.ConfluenceDavSessionProviderImpl.getConfluenceDavSession(ConfluenceDavSessionProviderImpl.java:123)
{code}
{code:java}
} catch (IOException ioe) {
                        log.error("Unable to get user name and/or password from the Authenticate header.", ioe);
                        throw new DavException(HttpServletResponse.SC_INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR, ioe);
                    }
{code}

Whichever class catching the exception doesn't treat it accordingly to output Log4J logging, therefore, the exception is just dumped into the logs in a raw way.

h2. Suggestion
To parse the SC_INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR accordingly so one could suppress it from being logged.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-68448].
  {panel}

Request for inclusion of the new Chromium based [Microsoft Edge|https://www.microsoftedgeinsider.com/en-us/] in Confluence supported platform.

Although the official [SAML standards|http://docs.oasis-open.org/security/saml/v2.0/saml-core-2.0-os.pdf] do not require it, many IdPs require a signed AuthNRequest for security reasons.

However, Confluence DC (with the Atlassian SAML SSO plugin) is sending an auth request like this one and doesn't have an option to sign it:
{code:java}
DEBUG [http-nio-8017-exec-7] [onelogin.saml2.authn.AuthnRequest] <init> AuthNRequest -->2019-11-06 10:34:38,997 DEBUG [http-nio-8017-exec-7] [onelogin.saml2.authn.AuthnRequest] <init> AuthNRequest --><samlp:AuthnRequest xmlns:samlp="urn:oasis:names:tc:SAML:2.0:protocol" xmlns:saml="urn:oasis:names:tc:SAML:2.0:assertion" ID="ONELOGIN_cc1deb92-97e7-451c-abd2-0bf93ddbd382" Version="2.0" IssueInstant="2019-11-06T18:34:38Z" Destination="https://my.idp.com/idp/SSO.saml2" ProtocolBinding="urn:oasis:names:tc:SAML:2.0:bindings:HTTP-POST" AssertionConsumerServiceURL="https://my.confluence.com/plugins/servlet/samlconsumer"> <saml:Issuer>https://my.confluence.com</saml:Issuer></samlp:AuthnRequest>
{code}
Thereby, authentication requests to IdPs that require the signature will fail with this error:
{code:java}
ERROR [http-nio-8017-exec-11] [onelogin.saml2.authn.SamlResponse] isValid The status code of the Response was not Success, was urn:oasis:names:tc:SAML:2.0:status:Requester -> Signature required
{code}

h3. Summary

When starting Confluence 7.0.4, this appears in {{catalina.out}}
{code:java}
[${confluence.context.path}/synchrony-proxy] does not meet these criteria and has been changed to [/${confluence.context.path}/synchrony-proxy]
{code}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Start Confluence-7.0.4

h3. Workaround

Edit the file {{server.xml}} and change the {{path}} attribute to start with a / (slash) {{path="/${confluence.context.path}/synchrony-proxy"}}
{code:xml}
<Context path="${confluence.context.path}/synchrony-proxy" docBase="../synchrony-proxy" debug="0" reloadable="false" useHttpOnly="true">
    <Valve className="org.apache.catalina.valves.StuckThreadDetectionValve" threshold="60" />
</Context>
{code}

h3. Problem Definition
External process pool does not take in space PDF header and footer customizations for table of contents page. Customizations can be picked up when not using external process pool.

{code:title=Sample space PDF Header customization}
      <div style="margin-top: 10.0mm;">
       <h1>Custom Header</h1>
      </div>
{code}

{code:title=Sample space PDF Footer customization}
      <div style="margin-bottom: 10.0mm;">
      <h1>Custom Footer</h1>
      </div>   
{code}

{code:title=Sample PDF Export Stylesheet}
div.toc{
   page:toc;
}  
{code}

h3. Workaround
Disable external process pool with system property *pdf.export.sandbox.disable*, per [PDF export in Confluence Data Center|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/pdf-export-in-confluence-data-center-958779100.html].

h3. Issue Summary
Confluence can display the wrong GMT information if the User Time Zone is under Daylight Savings.

h3. Issue Impact
There's no impact aside from wrong information being displayed to users on their Profile. Pages and blogs are saved with the right time information.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Login to Confluence as any user.
# Click on the Profile Picture in the right upper corner.
# Click on Profile.
# Click on the Settings Tab.
# Observe that Eastern Time is displayed as GMT-0500 even though from March to November it is supposed to be GMT-0400 due to DST - This is one example, other timezones may be affected as well:
!Screen Shot 2019-10-25 at 15.45.01.png|thumbnail!

h3. Expected Results
Confluence should be considering the DST offset to display the right GMT on that screen when the user timezone is affected by DST.

h3. Why this happens
Confluence is leveraging the [Java Time Zone getRawOffeset|https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/TimeZone.html#getRawOffset()] method. It does return GMT-0500 as EST Timezone. It then parse it to display the information to users on screen:
{code:java}
    public String getDisplayOffset() {
        int offset = getRawOffset();
        String sign = offset < 0 ? "-" : "+";
        offset = Math.abs(offset);
        int millis = offset % 1000;
        offset = (offset - millis) / 1000;
        int seconds = offset % 60;
        offset = (offset - seconds) / 60;
        int minutes = offset % 60;
        offset = (offset - minutes) / 60;
        int hours = offset;
        return MessageFormat.format("{0}{1,number,00}{2,number,00}",
                sign, Integer.valueOf(hours), Integer.valueOf(minutes));
    }
{code}

Confluence should have been leveraging the _observesDaylightTime_ and _getDSTSavings_ methods as well in order to consider DST offsets when building the display information to users. Possible solution below:
{code:java}
public static String getDisplayOffset() 
    {
        if (wrappedTimeZone.observesDaylightTime())
        {
            int offset = (wrappedTimeZone.getRawOffset()+wrappedTimeZone.getDSTSavings());
            String sign = offset < 0 ? "-" : "+";
            offset = Math.abs(offset);
            int millis = offset % 1000;
            offset = (offset - millis) / 1000;
            int seconds = offset % 60;
            offset = (offset - seconds) / 60;
            int minutes = offset % 60;
            offset = (offset - minutes) / 60;
            int hours = offset;
            return MessageFormat.format("{0}{1,number,00}{2,number,00}", sign, Integer.valueOf(hours), Integer.valueOf(minutes));
        }
        else
        {
            int offset = (wrappedTimeZone.getRawOffset());
            String sign = offset < 0 ? "-" : "+";
            offset = Math.abs(offset);
            int millis = offset % 1000;
            offset = (offset - millis) / 1000;
            int seconds = offset % 60;
            offset = (offset - seconds) / 60;
            int minutes = offset % 60;
            offset = (offset - minutes) / 60;
            int hours = offset;
            return MessageFormat.format("{0}{1,number,00}{2,number,00}", sign, Integer.valueOf(hours), Integer.valueOf(minutes));
        }
    }
{code}

h3. Workaround
None
